default&#xa0;defaultWritten Evidence Submitted by Angela Cross-defaultDurrantdefault [PHS0037]default&#xa0;default              default              default              default              default              defaultQuestion 11default&#xa0;default11
default              
defaultThe relationship between the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman and the individual citizen ought to continue to be one through which individuals can complain direct about health service issues.  
default&#xa0;
default11.1
default              
defaultThere is, however, arguably a case for a single health and social care complaints handling body.  As mentioned earlier, many individuals, e.g. in residential homes, receive some level of healthcare as well as social care while under the aegis of social services.  A single body ought to investigate these ‘dual’ cases of care because neither social workers nor local authority officers can address healthcare matters, which go well beyond following administrative processes and procedures.
default&#xa0;default11.2
default              
defaultThe Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman should continue to report to Parliament on the standard of service offered to the public;  to raise issues;  provide feedback on what has been learned from casework, etc.  However, the Ombudsman should also report on themes in complaints, dissatisfaction and comments 
defaultabout the Ombudsman’s office
default and comparisons year on year to demonstrate whether or not the Ombudsman’s own practice has changed as a result, and/or where there is persistent repetition of the same kind of complaint.
default&#xa0;
default11.3
default              
defaultThe
default Public Administration Select Committee ought to continue in its ‘investigative’ role regarding the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman.  This can ensure a light is shone on issues that emerge through contact with the Select Committee or as a result of official reports, and so on.
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 12default&#xa0;
default12
default              
defaultProviding evidence is essential if a complaint is to be made.  Whereas this stage of making a complaint falls outside considerations about complaints systems, the stage itself is a crucial part of a complaint.  However, obtaining that evidence is sometimes difficult if not impossible, despite individuals’ rights to it.  It also affects the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman’s effectiveness in handling complaints inadequately dealt with elsewhere.
default&#xa0;
default12.1
default              
defaultHealth and social care providers withhold information very often because of varied interpretation and 
defaultmis
default-use of Acts of Parliament, which are designed to allow individuals access.  This practice denies individuals any prospect of either corroborating or even making a complaint.  For example, there are insurmountable obstacles preventing relevant personal information being obtained by individuals despite the rights conferred by the Data Protection Act.  [Until guidance from the Department of Health changed, information sought by Executors via the Access to Health Records (of the Deceased) Act 1990 was unnecessarily difficult and in many cases impossible.]  Furthermore, by default, the obstacles are condoned by the Information Commissioner’s Office and by the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman.  
default&#xa0;
default12.2
default              
defaultThe Data Protection Act (DPA)1998, is meant to enable individuals to see personal information held on themselves:  it also confers the right for them to correct any factual inaccuracies in the records.  However, the Data Protection Act (DPA)1998 Subject Access Modification (Social Work) Order 2000, Statutory Instrument 2000, No. 415 remains open to different interpretation and consequently is easily 
defaultmis
default-used. This Statutory Instrument states that personal data may sometimes be withheld, but only in circumstances where the disclosure would be likely to prejudice the carrying out of social work 
defaultdue to the serious physical or mental harm it would cause
default either to the data subject or a third party.  There is no obligation for social workers to seek medical opinion despite the fact that they are not medically trained.  Councils and social workers can use this exemption with impunity.  They do not have to prove serious physical or mental harm – they can just state it.   The DPA also gives individuals the right to correct factual 
defaultinaccuracies in their records.  They cannot, however, correct any factual inaccuracies without seeing what has been proffered as facts at the outset. 
defaultMis
default-use of the Statutory Instrument results in gross injustices the length and breadth of the country, as well as preventing access to evidence to enable individuals to make complaints.  (See example 1 attached.)
default&#xa0;
default12.3
default              
defaultWhen individuals complain to the Information Commissioner that personal information has been withheld, the default is to find in favour of the data processor (the body in jurisdiction) because the Information Commissioner states his office does not have the expertise to question social services.  ‘
defaultThe ICO does not have the expertise necessary ...’  
defaultto ‘
default...challenge the view or conclusions of a social work professional in terms of why they believe disclosure of certain information would cause harm.’*
default  The public can only wonder why the Information Commissioner does not ‘buy in’ that expertise as necessary, and as recommended for NHS complaints in the Francis Report.  On complaining to the Parliamentary and Health Ombudsman a complainant will find that the Ombudsman supports the Information Commissioner because the Ombudsman “would not seem (it) appropriate for the ICO to challenge a professional opinion”.^  The public could be forgiven for concluding that no-one can question social services opinions.  The lack of necessary expertise to investigate and, where appropriate, challenge these opinions means that the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman cannot ever be effective in handling these sorts of complaints.  
default&#xa0;
default12.4
default              
defaultThe only recourse is to the court, but extremely few complainants can afford to take that path.  Consequently, victims of these flaws are 
defaultleft abandoned as
default ‘collateral damage’, regardless of the lasting effect on them.   At the very least, the guidance and/or Statutory Instruments pertaining to the Data Protection Act need re-wording to prevent individuals being denied the means (a) to comment or complain about public services and (b) to prevent people from never discovering what is in the data being held on them or the opportunity to correct factual inaccuracies.  This would reduce considerably the complaints reaching the Information Commissioner’s Office and subsequently reaching the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman, both of which ought to reduce costs.
default&#xa0;
default12.5
default              
defaultDiffering interpretations of the Access to Health Records (of the Deceased) Act 1990 has also prevented key evidence being obtained to make a complaint about the care of a person who died.  Delays surrounding the various interpretations made it virtually impossible to bring a complaint to a hospital let alone to escalate it to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman.  (See example 2.)
default&#xa0;
default12.6
default              
defaultThe case examples attached demonstrate the powerlessness of individuals caught up in complaints about councils/social services, withholding personal information despite the DPA, associated complaints to the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) and to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman.    
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 13default&#xa0;
default13
default              
defaultThe relationship between MPs and the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman ought to allow independence from each other while enabling co-ordination.  In some ways, MPs can be seen as giving advice about whether, how or when to complain.  There is merit in retaining the MP ‘filter’ because its removal could adversely affect complainants who may clearly need a kind of sponsor.  Removing the role could also reduce the ‘intelligence’ an MP has about serious issues some of her/his constituents face.
default&#xa0;
default13.1
default              
defaultHowever, it may be that MPs need to hone investigation or ‘triage’ skills of their own.  This might mean some form of coaching perhaps, or the opportunity occasionally to buy in expertise.  Nonetheless, all efforts should be made to avoid MPs being perceived, if not used, as additional, unpaid staff for the ombudsman.
default&#xa0;
default*  Response from ICO 2011
default^
default Response from PHSO 2011
default[Examples derived from acting as voluntary advocate.]
default&#xa0;
defaultExample 1
default&#xa0;
default(
defaulti
default)
default              
defaultAn individual needed personal information held by a local council in order to seek redress for being appallingly wrongly accused of abusing a family member.  The family member had been cared for by the individual for more than 20 years and had survived an incurable condition because of her care (confirmed by medical consultants dealing with the condition).  The case was unsubstantiated and closed.  The complainant sought personal information to enable the individual to complain to the LGO.  The council had concealed the details of the accusations through severe redaction of the records.  
default              
default(ii)
default              
defaultThe individual complained to the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) that the council 
defaultmis
default-used the Data Protection Act (DPA)1998, Subject Access Modification (Social Work) Order 2000, Statutory Instrument 2000, No. 415 to refuse to divulge the specific allegations that were made.  This Statutory Instrument states that personal data may sometimes be withheld only in circumstances where the disclosure would be likely to prejudice the carrying out of social work 
defaultdue to the serious physical or mental harm it would cause
default either to the data subject or a third
default party.  There is no 
defaultobligation 
defaultfor social workers to seek medical opinion and in this case none was sought.  Some of the records that were redacted by the council were later divulged by one of the third party organisations involved in the case.  No harm whatsoever was caused and social work continued untrammelled. The full detail, however, remained ‘secret’.
default&#xa0;
default(iii)
default              
defaultThe ICO could not deal adequately with the complaint stating that  ‘
defaultThe ICO does not have the expertise necessary ...’  
defaultto ‘
default...challenge the view or conclusions of a social work professional in terms of why they believe disclosure of certain information would cause harm.’
default  Moreover, the ICO stated that where there are opposing views, the ICO ‘..
defaultwill usually give the benefit of the doubt to the party whose (data) processing has been called into question.’
default **  
default&#xa0;
default(iv)
default              
defaultSubsequently, the individual complained to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman (in 2011) who considered that she had no means of challenging the opinion of social workers that harm would not ensue if records were disclosed.  She decided not to carry out an investigation.
default&#xa0;
default(v)
default              
defaultThe complainant has never been told what the specific allegations against her were, even though the case was closed because it was unsubstantiated.  She cannot correct any factual inaccuracies to set the record straight. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
