defaultCase review letter 2011
default&#xa0;
defaultAddendum
default&#xa0;
default(vi)
default              
defaultIt is worthy of note that over 26,000 people were victims of unsubstantiated allegations of abusing vulnerable adults in 2011-12***.  [A further 23,500 cases were inconclusive or not determined, which also casts doubt on these 23,500 safeguarding referrals also.]  Of the unsubstantiated 26,000 individuals wrongly subjected to safeguarding investigations and the horrific treatment they received during the process, no doubt subsequently many would have wanted to set their records straight.  However, as in paragraphs (ii) &amp; (iii) above, individuals cannot set records straight without seeing what the records and the actual allegations show.  In such circumstances, it is often argued that the accusers must be protected (though they are usually known anyway to the complainants, as in this case).  It seems that natural justice, let alone human rights, of the victims of unsubstantiated allegations are utterly ignored in these circumstances, and this practice effectively prevents individuals from making complaints. 
default&#xa0;
default(vii)
default              
defaultThere are no data concerning how many of victims of unsubstantiated allegations made successful Subject Access Requests in order to see their personal information.  Nonetheless, a 
defaulttotal of more than 26,000 wrongly accused individuals in just one year should not be ignored by the Public Administration Select Committee when considering the implications 
defaultof 
defaultvaried interpretation and 
defaultmis
default-use of legislation to block 
defaultthe path of making co
defaultmplaints.  It is highly probable
default that very, very few of the 26,000 ‘made it’ to the ICO let alone to complaining to the relevant ombudsman.
default 
default  
default              
default* * *  Health and Social Care Information Centre. “Abuse of Vulnerable Adults in England 2011-12.  Final Report.”   pp37-49
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultExample 2
default&#xa0;
default(
defaulti
default)
default              
defaultAn elderly resident in a care home died in her residential care home in 2005 shortly after two out-patient appointments to the local hospital.  The consultant told the lady’s daughter, who had accompanied her mother on the final appointment, that he would be in touch with her GP because her mother was not expected to survive much longer.  Soon after her death, it transpired from the care home records that none of the staff on duty on the day she died recognised that she was dying, despite a GP reportedly visiting the lady twice the day before she died.  There seemed to be confusion about what the GP had said to staff on his visits, and about what he prescribed and advised.  Later there was also confusion about what had transpired between the hospital consultant and the GP.  The lady’s son-in-law was her Executor and made a request to the Hospital Trust to see the records to reassure himself that nothing untoward had contributed to the patient’s death.
default&#xa0;
default(ii)
default              
defaultThe Hospital Trust took the view that the 1990 Act prevented access to the records of the deceased by anyone who was not making a claim arising from the patient’s death. The Act, Section 3 (1)(f) however, states that a deceased’s personal representative, namely her/his Executor, may have access or 
defaultsomeone with a claim against the estate
default.
default The Trust interpreted the subsection as only someone with a claim may have access, and that could include the Executor but only if he were making a claim arising out of the patient’s death.  The Executor was not making any claim.  After many months of correspondence, the Executor contacted the Chair of the Strategic Health Authority, who virtually dismissed the request for assistance on the grounds that the request was the business solely of the hospital in question.  The next year, the daughter wrote to her MP seeking help, who passed the letter to the then Minister for Health.  The Minister responded to confirm, unsurprisingly, what the Department of Health Guidance contained, namely that 
defaulteither the Executor or someone with a claim can have access to the records, 
defaultand that they are not mutually exclusive
default.
default  The Hospital Trust in question refused the request again some six months later, citing advice from its own solicitor, claiming that the Department and the Minister had misunderstood the Act and attendant guidance.  A complaint was made to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman who did not proceed to an investigation because it was thought the matter was one of interpretation of the law and, therefore, ought to be dealt with in court.
default&#xa0;
default(iii)
default              
defaultIn February 2010 the Department of Health’s new guidance on access to records of the deceased made very clear that the Executor of a will “
defaultis the only person who has an unqualified right of access to a deceased person’s records and need give no reason for applying for access to a record.”
default ^^   Five years had passed.  In November 2010, the Executor sent a copy of the guidance to the Hospital Trust.  It agreed to a further request from the Executor.  By that time the Trust had re-organised; there was a new Chief Executive and a new team dealing with complaints – and perhaps a new solicitor.  The consultant and the GP had retired.  The Trust considered it beyond its time limit to complain, and decided it had satisfied the long-standing complaint about the records.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
